Here is a large collection of quotes attributed to Lord Krishna, drawn mainly from the Bhagavad Gita and other scriptures:

1. **"You have the right to work, but never to the fruit of work."**
2. **"Change is the law of the universe. You can be a millionaire, or a pauper in an instant."**
3. **"Perform your duty equably, abandoning all attachment to success or failure. Such equanimity is called Yoga."**
4. **"When meditation is mastered, the mind is unwavering like the flame of a lamp in a windless place."**
5. **"A person can rise through the efforts of his own mind; or draw himself down, in the same manner. Because each person is his own friend or enemy."**
6. **"Delusion arises from anger. The mind is bewildered by delusion. Reasoning is destroyed when the mind is bewildered. One falls down when reasoning is destroyed."**
7. **"As a person puts on new garments, giving up old ones, the soul similarly accepts new material bodies, giving up the old and useless ones."**
8. **"For one who has conquered the mind, the mind is the best of friends, but for one who has failed to do so, the mind will remain the greatest enemy."**
9. **"The soul is neither born, and nor does it die."**
10. **"There is neither this world, nor the world beyond. Nor happiness for the one who doubts."**
11. **"The mind acts like an enemy for those who do not control it."**
12. **"For one who sees Me everywhere and sees everything in Me, I am never lost, nor is he ever lost to Me."**
13. **"One who has control over the mind is tranquil in heat and cold, in pleasure and pain, and in honor and dishonor, and is ever steadfast with the Supreme Self."**
14. **"Whatever happened, happened for the good. Whatever is happening, is happening for the good. Whatever will happen, will also happen for the good."**
15. **"The wise unify their consciousness and abandon the fruits of action, which frees them from the bondage of rebirth and leads them to the state beyond sorrow."**
16. **"When a man dwells on the objects of sense, he creates an attachment to them; attachment gives rise to desire, and desire breeds anger."**
17. **"As the heat of a fire reduces wood to ashes, the fire of knowledge burns to ashes all karma."**
18. **"The power of God is with you at all times; through the activities of mind, senses, breathing, and emotions; and is constantly doing all the work using you as a mere instrument."**
19. **"Whatever you do, whatever you eat, whatever you offer in sacrifice, whatever you give, whatever austerity you perform, do it as an offering to Me."**
20. **"When a person is devoted to something with complete faith, I unify his faith in that. Then, when his faith is completely unified, he gains the object of his devotion."**
21. **"I am time, the great destroyer of the world, and I have come here to engage all people."**
22. **"Man is made by his belief. As he believes, so he is."**
23. **"One who performs his duty without attachment, surrendering the results unto the Supreme Lord, is unaffected by sinful action, as the lotus is untouched by water."**
24. **"I am the origin of all creation. Everything proceeds from me. The wise who know this worship me with all their hearts."**
25. **"The mind is restless and difficult to restrain, but it is subdued by practice."**
26. **"A person who is not disturbed by the incessant flow of desires that enter like rivers into the ocean, which is ever being filled but is always still, can alone achieve peace, and not the person who strives to satisfy such desires."**
27. **"Whatever action is performed by a great man, common men follow in his footsteps, and whatever standards he sets by exemplary acts, all the world pursues."**
28. **"Out of compassion for them, I, who dwell within their hearts, destroy the darkness born of ignorance with the luminous lamp of knowledge."**
29. **"There are three gates to this self-destructive hell: lust, anger, and greed. Renounce these three."**
30. **"In this world, three gates lead to hell—the gates of passion, anger, and greed. Everyone should avoid them."**
31. **"I am the taste of water, the light of the sun and the moon, the syllable Om in the Vedic mantras; I am the sound in ether and ability in man."**
32. **"The knowledge of the absolute truth, the presence of God in all living beings, the feeling of oneness of the soul with the Supreme Being—these are the greatest wisdom."**
33. **"Those who have attained the highest perfection are freed from all dualities and delusions. They dwell in the self and have dedicated themselves to the welfare of all beings."**
34. **"The material world is bound by cause and effect. The wise person, by discerning and understanding this, cuts off the bonds of attachment and attains liberation."**
35. **"The path of spirituality is the path of truth, righteousness, and justice. This path leads to self-realization, which is the ultimate goal of life."**
36. **"The wise person, who has controlled the mind and senses, is the same in pleasure and pain, honor and dishonor, and who sees a lump of earth, a stone, and a piece of gold as all the same, is truly liberated."**
37. **"The wise person, who has attained true knowledge, sees all beings in the self, and the self in all beings. Such a person does not feel hate or attachment to anyone."**
38. **"A person is considered still further advanced when he regards honest well-wishers, affectionate benefactors, the neutral, mediators, the envious, friends and enemies, the pious and the sinners all with an equal mind."**
39. **"The senses are so strong and impetuous, O Arjuna, that they forcibly carry away the mind even of a man of discrimination who is endeavoring to control them."**
40. **"Such a liberated person is not attracted to material sense pleasure, but is always in a trance, enjoying the pleasure within. In this way, the self-realized person enjoys unlimited happiness, for he concentrates on the Supreme."**
41. **"The wise are free from doubts and dualities. They are self-controlled, engaged in selfless service, and always situated in the Self. They are not bound by material actions and reactions."**
42. **"A person who can control his senses and mind, who can see the same divine spirit in all living beings, and who has realized the oneness of the self with the Supreme Being, is considered a truly enlightened soul."**
43. **"By performing one’s natural duty, one achieves the highest good. Abandoning one’s natural duty out of fear or confusion is considered sinful."**
44. **"The wise person, who has attained self-realization, is not attached to the fruits of his actions. He performs his duties selflessly, without attachment, and thus attains peace and liberation."**
45. **"The wise are not deluded by the dualities of life. They are even-minded in success and failure, gain and loss, pleasure and pain. They have attained self-realization and are free from the bondage of karma."**
46. **"The wise person, who has realized the true nature of the self, is free from ego, attachment, and desires. He is at peace with himself and the world."**
47. **"The wise do not grieve for the living or the dead. They are aware of the eternal nature of the soul, which neither dies nor is born."**
48. **"The wise person, who has attained self-realization, is not affected by the changes in the material world. He remains undisturbed by the dualities of life and is always situated in the Self."**
49. **"The wise person, who has realized the oneness of the self with the Supreme Being, is free from all doubts and delusions. He is at peace with himself and the world."**
50. **"The wise person, who has controlled his mind and senses, is not affected by praise or criticism. He remains calm and composed in all situations."**
51. **"The wise person, who has attained self-realization, is not disturbed by the desires and attachments of the material world. He remains content and peaceful in all situations."**
52. **"The wise person, who has realized the true nature of the self, is not attached to the body or the material world. He is at peace with himself and the world."**
53. **"The wise person, who has attained self-realization, is free from the bondage of karma. He performs his duties selflessly, without attachment to the results."**
